</title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/5990/can-linux-i-name-my-dual-screens-always-the-same/?comment=5992#comment-5992</link><description>Its not a solution but you could minimize your problem by using variables: set $firstMonitor DVI-I-1 To use them: workspace 1 output $firstMonitor That way you only have to edit one entry per output per system...</description><pubDate>Wed, 13 May 2015 16:40:51 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/5990/can-linux-i-name-my-dual-screens-always-the-same/?comment=5992#comment-5992</guid></item><item><title>Answer by gurkensalat for &lt;p&gt;Question :   Is that an xrandr issue?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have one PC with several hard disks.
Some have Antergos, Manjaro, Archlinux or even Linux Mint.
All different kernels with just xorg or nVidia drivers.
But all of them have i3.&lt;/p&gt;

